comment._content: Gwendolyn Nash Gorman, Dec. 8, 1890 - Oct. 23, 1966 (www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GRid=70599927). An article about her engagement to Douglas Gorman is in The New York Times, October 14, 1911 There is a photo of her and her sister, Mrs. Culver McWilliam, in The sun., April 09, 1916, THIRD SECTION, Page 2. Mrs. Culver McWilliam was Eleanor A. Nash, see The sun., April 02, 1916, THIRD SECTION, Image 22, Col. 6. Douglas Gorman was a son of William Henry Gorman (August 29, 1843 – July 7, 1915) (en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Henry_Gorman) and a nephew of Senator Arthur Pue Gorman (March 11, 1839 – June 4, 1906) (en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arthur_Pue_Gorman).

comment.author: 23103743@N05
comment._content: Princeton Alumni Weekly, Vol 44, No 8., Nov 12, 1943, page 10 books.google.com/books?id=CRRbAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA29-IA49&a... indicates that Douglas (Princeton '03) had at least two children, sons Douglas, Jr, (Princeton '35) and Arthur (Princeton '38). A Princeton yearbook entry for another son, Edmund, www.e-yearbook.com/yearbooks/Princeton_University_Nassau_... says "EDMUND NASH GORMAN Ted Gorman was born July 2?, 1914, in Catonsville, Md. He is the son of Douglas Gorman ' 03, and Shirley Maud Gwendolen Nash. His father is president of the Cumberland Coal Company. He has four brothers, one of whom is Douglas Gorman, Jr., ' 35-" So a starting hypothesis is that these two children are Douglas, Jr and Edmund, the oldest of five Gorman boys.
